#achievement(title: [Food Insecurity as an Emergent Disease Burden in ME/CFS and Long COVID])[
Cross-national evidence from multiple large-scale studies now establishes food insecurity as a measurable, independent consequence of ME/CFS and Long COVID—adding a nutritional dimension to the well-documented socioeconomic impact of these diseases. (Certainty: 0.75; evidence base: 3 large-scale studies, 1 ME/CFS-specific survey)

*Evidence Base.*
- *Dey et al. 2026*—First ME/CFS-specific food insecurity survey, New Zealand: ME/CFS and Long COVID patients report elevated rates of marginal, moderate, and severe food insecurity, with disease severity predicting food access difficulties and disability benefit inadequacy compounding the effect @dey2026foodinsecurity. (Certainty: 0.65)
- *Lin et al. 2025*—NHIS 2022–2023 (n = 21,631): food insecurity associated with 73% higher odds of current Long COVID (aOR 1.73, 95% CI 1.39–2.15). 15% of food-insecure adults reported current Long COVID vs. 7% of food-secure adults. SNAP participation attenuated the association, and food-insecure individuals had 30% lower odds of recovery from prior Long COVID @lin2025longcovidfoodinsecurity. (Certainty: 0.80)
- *Datta 2025*—BRFSS 2022 (n = 271,076): Long COVID independently associated with 1–11 percentage-point increases in food insecurity across income and education strata. Employment loss and reduced work hours mediated 6–20% of the effect @datta2025longcovidfinancial. (Certainty: 0.75)
- *Feldman 2025*—NIH RECOVER adult cohort: social determinants of health, including food access, independently associated with Long COVID risk @feldman2025sdohlongcovid. (Certainty: 0.70)
- *Bowden 2026*—New Zealand nationwide cross-sectional (n = 1,902 ME/CFS on benefit): only 18.3% employed vs. 83.8% general population; 64.7% on Supported Living Payment @bowden2026mecfslabourmarket. This employment gap is the primary mechanism through which food insecurity arises in ME/CFS—absent adequate income, nutritional adequacy becomes compromised. (Certainty: 0.75)

*Interpretation.*
The direction of effect is bidirectional: ME/CFS and Long COVID cause disability and income loss → food insecurity; conversely, food insecurity may impair recovery through nutritional inadequacy and increased allostatic load @vester2026burdenreview. The employment-mediation evidence (Datta 2025) supports the causal pathway from disease to food insecurity. The food-insecurity-to-recovery pathway (Lin 2025: aOR 0.70 for recovery among food-insecure) is observational and needs interventional confirmation.

*Limitations.*
All food-insecurity data are self-reported; most studies are cross-sectional (causal direction cannot be established definitively). The ME/CFS-specific evidence comprises one survey from New Zealand (n unreported in abstract). No studies examine food insecurity specifically in severe or bedbound ME/CFS patients, who are likely at highest risk. The nutritional consequences of food insecurity (specific micronutrient deficiencies) have not been systematically assessed in ME/CFS populations. No interventional studies test whether food assistance programs improve ME/CFS outcomes. No data from low- or middle-income countries.

*Falsifiability.*
This claim would be refuted if: (a) prospective studies find no independent association between ME/CFS and incident food insecurity after controlling for income, disability status, and pre-existing nutritional status; or (b) interventional trials show that resolving food insecurity (via SNAP, MTM, or benefit adequacy) does not improve ME/CFS functional outcomes relative to matched controls.

*Consequence:* Food insecurity affects whether patients can afford adequate nutrition—a prerequisite for every treatment and management strategy described in this paper. Clinicians should screen for food access barriers, and disability benefit adequacy is a modifiable policy lever. For patients, this adds an objective, measurable dimension to the disease burden narrative that is independent of contested pathophysiology.
] <ach:food-insecurity-disease-burden>
